Title: All Fours
Author: Miranda July
My Review: This book delivers in a way that only Miranda July knows how. I’ve read her first book, The First Bad Man at least three times on account of it being the only book I owned from ages 18-23 (this is a joke but not really). Maybe because of this, reading this novel felt like going inside my best friend’s head and defending her 100% despite not fully agreeing with her actions. Just the same as the protagonist in her first novel, I don’t understand her and yet I understand her better than I know myself. Throughout this book, she’s doing stuff that I would never do, and yet I am her, and you know what.. I AM her. Not that she is me, but i am her. When I read this book, I was her. If that makes sense.

Title: Perfect Days
Author: Raphael Montes
My Review:
I first read this book when it came out around 2016 when I was 18 years old and new to reading books written for adults and not YA. More than any piece of media I’ve ever consumed, the ending of this book has stuck with me for YEARS. Creating a visceral fear of, and almost certainty that I would one day end up paralyzed from the waist down. Even now, eight or so years after I first read it, aspects of this book pop up in my subconscious.

After rereading, I think I give some credit to this book for shaping my taste in media, I’m grateful to this book for influencing my sensibilities, and I recommend reading it, especially as an entryway into the genre, but for me, at this stage in my life, I’d say it was pretty average.

Title: She's Not Sorry
Author: Mary Kubica
My Review:
Wow I really liked this book, I think it was almost perfect. I would have rated this five stars but there was just sooooo much happening.
I’m able to suspend my disbelief that so many intense and strange deceptive things can happen to one woman all at the same time, because it’s a story it’s not real life. But at the same time some of the twists were a little…… much? Not saying I didn’t eat it up or that I disliked it at all, but the amount of stuff that gets revealed in the last 50 or so pages of this book had my head spinning.
That being said, my heart was actually racing during those last 50 pages and I read this book so fast and savored it. I liked the main character and I liked the story, I wasn’t expecting any of the twists although they were a little “tropey” and looking back I can see that, but this book actually satisfied me greatly and i kind of want to re-read it knowing how it ends.
4.5 stars would recommend

In regards to other people’s reviews on here- I don’t know what you’re talking about that nothing happens until 70% in… a lot of stuff happens while the climax does come late in the book, that doesn’t mean the parts that arent the climax aren’t important? Not to be a dick but do you guys not like reading or something?

Title: Iona Iverson's Rules for Commuting
Author: Clare Pooley
My Review: Was in desperate need of a palette cleanser after reading a few stinker thrillers in a row, stumbled onto this perfect little book with characters I loved and a sweet little low stakes story that still felt very important to tell.  Emmie’s storyline gave this a perfect amount of mystery that kept my broken thriller pilled brain engaged but I overall really fell in love with the characters, especially Martha who gets everything she deserves (positive). Love a book where everyone gets a happy ending.

Title: One Perfect Couple
Author: Ruth Ware
My Review: This was marketed for fans of the bachelor or love island but that is not how I would classify this. I went in expecting it to be like a reality show and I was a little sad when it turned out to be more of a lord of the flies survival story. However I quickly got over the fact that I would have loved to see how the reality show actually went and I actually enjoyed this book. It wasn’t my favorite book I’ve ever read but I’ve also read much worse. Not bad, 3 stars.

Title: Kill for Me, Kill for You
Author: Steve Cavanagh
My Review:
People really liked this apparently, I don’t see why.
I really did not enjoy this. It was not fun, it was not satisfying. There were about two points where I was intrigued, and that’s about it.
I just could not get myself to /care/ about what happened. I didn’t care about the characters, I was constantly trying to remember who was who and I couldn’t keep it straight. It took too long to get to the point. It made me upset and it didn’t make me happy, it felt like a chore to read.
The best part was the reveal of the timelines, I really liked that. But I’m sorry that was the only thing I liked.
The final reveal at the end of Mr blue eyes was so rushed that I almost missed it as I speed read this book just to finish it.
And she BURNS her daughters TOY? WHY did she do that, did I miss something?

And if I’m being honest, not that this is the most important thing, and feel free to call me an elitist nyc fuck, but the way this author writes about New York City was just so deluded and ridiculous. It reminds me of the way a child would describe an imaginary life in New York. I read this book almost entirely on the nyc subway and never once did I swipe my “MTA card” (because that is not what we call it), and I guarantee you that there are few to no “New Yorkers” who even know that there is a clock in grand central. I’ve been an nyc local all my life and I saw grand central for the first time maybe two years ago. We don’t think of the 34th st macys as an “institution”.
When I saw in the author bio at the end that the author was from Ireland it made sense, just set the book in Ireland, or even London.
Would not recommend at all.

Title: The Idiot
Author: Elif Batuman
My Review:
“I kept thinking about the uneven quality of time- the way it was almost always so empty, and then with no warning came a few days that felt so dense and alive and real that it seemed indisputable that that was what life was, that it’s real nature had finally been revealed. But then time passed and unthinkably grew dead again, and it turned out that that fullness had been an aberration and might never come back”


With the speed that I’ve been reading books this year, taking almost an entire month to finish a book would indicate that it wasn’t engaging. But….. this couldn’t be farther from the truth.
This book really SAT with me. I’d find myself thinking about it in a different way than I think about most fiction books, I’m not thinking about the story but I’m thinking about what I read. The Idiot is literally a rabbit hole of a book, I highlighted so many passages, so much of it was stuff I had never thought about before, but now I’m like “this is me now”. If that makes any sense.

This book literally…. had me by the balls. I really want to write a thoughtful review of this later but for now I’ll say that this would have been five stars for me but I got a little lost in the last third of the book, it does pick back up though, and the last line of the book really did give me a full body reaction, I’m not being DRAMATIC

EDIT - I’m screaming crying throwing up to find out there’s a sequel…..

Title: Listen for the Lie
Author: Amy Tintera
My Review:
“We might all be dead soon, but that seems like too much to hope for”

Really fun and quick read, more of a light thriller, nothing very scary but still full of shocking twists. I’m hard to please when it comes to a twist ending but I think this one actually holds up. No plot holes and everything does resolve in the end (which is a very basic standard to have but is not actually easy to find), ending was surprising but not unbelievable to a fault. The podcast sections were fun to read and I bet it’s done well in the audiobook.

This book came up a lot when I was looking for something else to read in the vein of First Lie Wins by Ashley Elston which I read earlier this year. It reminded me much more of None of This is True by Lisa Jewell or even Dark Places by Gillian Flynn.

Title: Help Wanted
Author: Adelle Waldman
My Review:
Months after I finished this book I find myself coming back to write a review which is rare because I don’t really have much to say about a lot of what I log on here.
I worked in order fulfillment at target in college, and in pretty sure this book is supposed to be about target. The way the store operated under nightfall felt like magic, and getting a glimpse into the actual process was really intriguing.
Mostly this book is about the characters, which are rich and interesting, workplace fiction is one of my favorite things to read because of the details that emerge from the mundanity of life at work.
This book just works, highly recommend and will be rereading one day.

Title: The Fault in Our Stars
Author: John Green
My Review:
I am, of course, a very avid John Green fan. I believe he is not only one of the best YA writers, but also one of the best fiction writers in general, and while his books are technically listed under YA, they appeal to adults as well. This book is John Green at his finest, you become so attached to the characters and the settings that you will laugh, and cry, and feel all of the emotions that the main characters at the same time that they are feeling them. John does a great job of ending the book in a way that makes you think about everything that has happened and will happen in the future with the story which is nice because it lets you interpret what will happen after the book ends. I have found myself still thinking about this book four months after I first read it, and ended up reading it again a second time because it has hit a soft spot somewhere inside me.
I cannot say enough good things about this book, please go pick it up right now and read the entire thing.
